                  <h4 class="takeaways__subheading">Avoid saying "prototype"</h4>
                </div>
                <p>‚ÄúPrototype‚Äù continues to be a loaded word these days, and I find it‚Äôs best to refer to it as a ‚Äúlearning tool‚Äù because it sets expectations more accurately. The thing we build at the end of a Sprint is not a fully-fledged prototype, or replica of what we intend to build. It‚Äôs a tool we use to test our riskiest assumptions with our users.</p><p>During this round of interviews, instead of calling it a prototype, I called it ‚Äúa visual way for us to keep asking you questions.‚Äù This really loosened up the participants, and set the tone that we are really there to learn about <em>them</em>.</p>
              </div>
          </li>
          <li class="item-details item-details--takeaways">
            <span class="item-details__number">02</span>
              <div class="item-details__copy">
                <div class="item-details__header">
                  <h4 class="takeaways__subheading">Create a safe space</h4>
                </div>
                <p>When you‚Äôre facilitating a Product Design Sprint, it‚Äôs so important to create a safe space for your participants.</p><p> Being that this idea was in its earliest stages, it was crucial for us to hear Cherie‚Äôs entire thought process and all the things that led to her decision to work with us. This helped show her that we are now her teammates, ready to join her on her journey.</p>
              </div>
          </li>
          <li class="item-details item-details--takeaways">
            <span class="item-details__number">03</span>
